@Funakounasoul (I can't imagine coming out to my parents....)

That's an... interesting fear. No hate or judgment. Just... interesting.

All I know is I feel like I was cheated out of a lot of crucial teenage development.

Which probably explains why I'm so rambunctiously vivacious as a 30 year old.

Well, to be fair

I didn't exactly drive until I was 23 and I lived in the middle of nowhere. And they also pushed academia really hard since elementary.

So maybe that's actually something they wanted? My parents got married in their 40's so...

Maybe I've forgotten some crucial lore element.... But AFAIK, they just... never asked.

No "are you dating?" or "when you getting married?" or "when will we be grandparents?" rhetoric. Like.. at all.

Not in the sense that my parents were super cool about it.

It was just... I didn't date. At all. (Excluding an online relationship I never told them about.) And they didn't seem to question it. Ever. Plenty of same-sex friends though.

Makes me wonder what they thought of that.

Thinking about it... it's a little bit funny.

Relationships and orientation were the one thing that WASN'T a massive pain point growing up, hahah.

(Third time writing that's the charm. I swear I can English.)

So, what my brain insists is reality and what other queer people experience corroborate... but both are disparate from my actual lived experience.

But I'm not an impostor. So all that really leaves is "outsider".

In the back of my mind, I suppose it's like I've been conditioned to expect fighting and hiding, so the lack of that presses the "what the hell" klaxon in the back of my brain. It makes me question things. It makes me... uncomfortable in a way.

That's what I mean by "weird".

So in a way, I did kind of learn through my own battles this idea of who you are being something you hide or fight for --something fought against.

So this distinct lack of having to do much hiding+fighting for stuff like orientation and gender just

Makes me feel weird.

Mind you, my childhood wasn't full of love and acceptance. It was that brand of hell for different reasons. My parents wouldn't call me my preferred name. My hobbies and passions were fought and begrudged. Etc.

And that WAS for a kid ostensibly cis and straight at the time.

It's certainly not right to think of harassment and assault as anything remotely adjacent to a necessary component of queer life. If anything, that somebody can actualize their queer self *without* any of that is a sign of progress, right?

But it's still a weird feeling.

The more I read into the past and present lives of other queer people, the more that "outsider" sentiment itches.

In short, I don't want to fling it around all willy-nilly (hah, that's some choice wording) and ruffle feathers, but I also don't want to go through the effort of making a nice little discrete "adult corner" (again) if it's just going to be devoid of patronage.

That latter sentiment is further compounded by the fact that --honestly-- I would paywall it.

Why? It's "the way". Most artists I know seem to do that and I agree with the practice for no substantive reason beyond that I just do.

I think it would be a faux pas against my followers/mutuals if I went from being relatively tame-ish to suddenly posting substantial NSFW --even with the media flagging.

But I also don't think I'm at a skill level where I could just post it aside and expect people to follow.

So this erroneous belief that a trans person should have shown "signs" as a kid is doubly wrong.

Not just because of people who simply showed no signs, but also because it implies people are innately capable of recognizing signs --hubris in a remarkably transphobic society.

It's impossible to have that moment of honesty where you wonder if these traits have underlying implications, when your worldview precludes the notion of such implications existing.

And so, the signs ultimately just... aren't. A sign is only a sign if people understand it.

Growing up, I've had my fair share of "hmmm 🤔" things that could be considered "signs".

But whether or not they meant anything, it's impossible to question yourself when your taught worldview says anything beyond cis-normative is just weirdos being perverse and wrong.

TBF, I don't know what the trans scene was like in the 90's.

But I was acquainted with the caricatures and misunderstandings and slurs WAY before I was ever acquainted with real trans people and real trans lore.

Up until college, my sphere of awareness didn't include trans at all in ANY kind of authentic capacity.

Like, at BEST, all there was in my sphere was occasional godawful caricatured propaganda that would be derided viciously. https://t.co/0qeMpfulXb

I suppose the only real effective answer is "don't overthink, just do".

Creativity sure can be exponentially harder than it needs to be when you're an engineer who likes the question "why?"

It could be that those finite spaces exist in a spacial distortion --entire bounds of land existing in a smaller area of space. Same sun, same moon, same universe.

But I think that would create an even worse headache with boundaries and transiting into and out of those regions.

It could be that the other worlds are just nebulous finite space but... what would encapsulate them? And wouldn't it be a bit unfair that humans get the whole kit and caboodle while other species just get some weird kingdom-like chunk?

However, there's a "hiccup" to this design in the form of me having no idea what the true shape of these other worlds should be.

It could be parallel Earths, but I don't particularly want entire parallel planets --much less with entire parallel universes surrounding them.

But each overlapping space isn't necessarily our world overlapping with the same other world each time.

There might be dozens of different worlds overlapping each other.

It certainly sounds silly --"DyneBarn". And maybe it gives some science person somewhere a headache.

But it kind of has this satisfying goofiness to it that feels right. Even when they're serious, giant robots are silly. So I think it's a fitting choice (for now?)

It was halfway easy enough. I always intended for ダイン to mean Dyne (like the unit). But I couldn't commit to what the hell バーン was.

But TIL that there's a quasi-SI unit in particle physics literally called a "Barn".

And y'know what? I honestly say LET'S GO FOR IT, hahah.

Honestly, I could've just decided the big guy was named DainBaan and called it a day. But obviously that's not how that works. There's ALWAYS an English name.

E.g., マジンガー is "majingaa" but we call it "Mazinger".

So, y'know, naturally ダインバーン had to "be" something too.

A good super robot has a "good sounding" name.

It can be noticeably rooted or just seem like gibberish. Either way, it has to roll off the tongue and it has to be fun to shout!

So of course I went and picked some "good sounding" phonemes:

ダインバーン
<dainbaan>

Dyne's super form isn't really a secret since I drew a (no longer canon) take on it 2 years ago.

But I never had a fully "localized" name for it. I had ideas but no commitment. Fortunately, thanks to some innocent googling, I might have an answer, lol.

Whatever the case

I did NOT consent to adulthood requiring me to learn how to navigate bureaucracy, contract law, and End Stage Capitalist Nonsense.

But HERE I AM ANYWAY learning this stuff!

So.. y'know...

Just casually waiting to see if I have to bleed dry even more for this stupid crap.

This sort of thing is called "balance billing".

Technically speaking, a law went into effect at the beginning of this year to disallow certain kinds of balance billing related to the egregious concept of "out of network providers".

But that's not pertinent to me, I don't think.

So that's $100 unaccounted for. What is Provider to do?

Well, maybe they don't actually care. Maybe $850 is actually a 400% markup so $750 is still making bank.

OR they could decide to... bill *You* for it! Sucks to be you, American jerkwad! Vive la Capitalism!

Yup.

Where it gets stupid is that last part is often the first part. Provider *assumes* based on.. I don't know... that they can get $800 out of Insurance, so they *assume* they only need to charge You $50 and bill that upfront.

But whoops! Insurance only pays $700 this time!

Gamified as in:

> You get Thing
> Thing costs $850
> Provider tells Insurance "Thing costs $1200" 
> Insurance says "BS, it's worth $800" and pays $800 
> Insurance tells You "we paid $800, you owe $400"
> Provider only charges You $50

At least, that's MY understanding.

I mean... it doesn't necessarily mean I will be. The EOB is just a statement that the insurance paid X amount and thinks I owe Y remaining to the provider.

AFAIK, the provider can certainly disagree since it's all BS gamified math, rather than real commerce.

I do not like when the EOB says one value and the actual bill I paid says another value, especially when the bill I paid is a LOWER value.

I do not wish to be surprise billed additional money for WANTING TO LIVE please okay thanks.

In conclusion: GaoGaiGar is feel-good hi-tech crashy bashy robot smashy that preaches a good moral. If you love robots, please watch it.

Unless you are photo-sensitive to flashing lights. There are lots of flashing lights.

Or can only watch dubbed. The dub was never finished.

And the show does remind the viewer of this at points, by either having GaoGaiGar lose a round, or win purely through force of will and raw strength.

Spoiler: ever wanted to see a giant robot cast aside all the fancy gimmicks and rip an enemy to shreds with its own bare hands?

Ultimately, the intent is to convey that the tools and upgrades and gimmicks aren't the only things that save the day. While they absolutely play an important role, the REAL credit still goes to the unyielding hearts of the Braves.

The tools are only as good as the user.

And the reason for that is that  growth in power is baked in "organically". GaoGaiGar and other Brave allies are powered by G-Stones that produce greater power in proportion to courage.

I.e., GaoGaiGar gets stronger purely through strengthening bonds and combat experience.

When it comes to robot upgrades, they are few and far between.

GaoGaiGar doesn't combine into anything bigger or get a whole bunch of extra parts or whatever. It gets one modest mid-season upgrade to its engine tech and StealthGao backpack.

That's about it.

Of the tools that ARE weapons, many aren't just "new thing with greater firepower". The quirk of Zonders is that their cores are imprisoned civilians. So many of the "Kill" moves are designed around safely extracting those cores.

They're still flashy, but it's TECHNICAL flashy.

There's also the Eraser Head, which can absorb energy from enemy attacks and harmlessly disperse it upward into space.

In a lot of ways, GaoGaiGar is conscientious of what a giant robot in a city means, and shows ways GGG strives to minimize the damage.

What I personally love most about GaoGaiGar, however, is its approach to technology and gear and upgrades.

Some tools in GaoGaiGar aren't weapons. The Dividing Driver, for example, is used to distort space to create a temporary battlefield in urban areas to minimize city damage.

The main theme of GaoGaiGar is indomitable bravery. With courage, anything is possible! If the chance of success isn't 0%, then bravery will make that chance 100%!

And with it, a heavy secondary theme of trust in your friends and allies, and faith in their own courage.

The King of Braves GaoGaiGar is the 8th and ultimately final entry in Sunrise's saga of Brave Robots.

Spanning 49 episodes, it told the story of the Gutsy Geoid Guard and its hero Cyborg Guy, in their fight against the evil alien Zonders that threaten Earth.

Happy Birthday to GaoGaiGar!

Too many tweets exhaust the brain and make it hard to be eloquent, so I'm shutting up here.

Make of my rant what you will. Maybe I'm unbearably naive. Or maybe there's wisdom to what I think.

Well, that's a bit awkwardly phrased.

What and how I draw are reflections of who I am. It hits hard to think the only way to be worth money is to change that.

Because it's not just one change. Or two. It's constant change. It's trying to "make" yourself worth others' time.

Finding my authentic self has been a life-long journey full of forgotten memories and self-doubt. Hell, it took me 30 years just to figure out my true name.

So it hits extra hard to feel like the only way I can get stronger and secure my place in the world is to give that up.

Because every bond I make is one I make through being authentically me --as messy and confusing and stupid as that me might be.

So my struggles and failures feel a lot like the world is telling me my authentic self isn't worth anything.

And I've made some friendships. I've met some people who genuinely do support me. And I never want to tarnish my gratitude for them.

But at the same time, it's exhausting to be ignored by such an exponentially larger amount of people.

Well, it's not guaranteed to happen. But I want to avoid that future no matter what.

Which is why my most selfish desire all this time has been community. I want to be wanted. Appreciated. Desired so much that people are willing to support me with even just a damned dollar.

I do what I can the best I can to stand on my own two feet and persist with my own strength.

But I fear this is one of those shounen battles where the hero uses all their strength to stay standing and then the villain reveals that was only a fraction of their power!

I got far. Farther than most. I got a degree (somehow). Found work that pays well enough to keep the roof above and food in the fridge (somehow).

But every day I wonder when that's going to come crashing down. When w/e part of this country decides "I'm done. Go fuck yourself."

TBH, I'm so tired of feeling like I have to "fight" for mutual aid. That I have to be "worthy" of it. Or maybe I'm just an ordinary un-special human being with the hubris to dare think I deserve anything more than what I earn with my own two hands.

Who knows.
